While functions can receive data and act upon it, it's equally as important to know functions can send back data. By using the keyword return, followed by data, we can retrive the "result" of a function and set that to a variable. function AddNumbers(number1, number2) local Result = number1 + number2 return Result
end local Sum = AddNumbers(2, 4)
print(Sum) As a note, it's important to know NOT to type anything after your return. Return essentially stops the current scope, and any code after that will error. With RLua, we can also return multiple values with return. function AddAndSubtractNumbers(number1, number2) local Sum = number1 + number2 local Difference = number1 - number2 return Sum, Difference
end local Sum, Diference = AddAndSubtractNumbers(8, 6)
print(Sum, Difference)
